{
  "doc_id": "4740",
  "text": "The brain interfaces with the environment through multiple sensory channels carrying information about different forms of environmental energy. Some of these inputs are processed separately, but others are combined to form a unified percept of the world. Such multisensory interactions are governed by a combination of stimulus characteristics such as intensity, timing, and spatial coincidence [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and higher-order cognitive functions such as semantic congruence [CITATION_4] and attention [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Interestingly, older adults show increased multisensory integration [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . One potential explanation for this increase is age-related changes in top-down regulation of multisensory interactions, specifically attention.",
